        <tr><td class="province">Quebec</td><td>GST + QST</td><td class="rate">5% + 9.975%</td><td>14.975%</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="province">Saskatchewan</td><td>GST + PST</td><td class="rate">5% + 6%</td><td>11%</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="province">Yukon</td><td>GST only</td><td class="rate">5%</td><td>5%</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h2>Step-by-Step: How to Calculate GST on an Invoice</h2>
    <p>Here's the exact 4-step process every Canadian business uses:</p>

    <h3>Step 1 — Calculate your subtotal</h3>
    <p>Add up the cost of all goods or services on the invoice before any tax. This is your <strong>subtotal</strong> (also called the "pre-tax amount"). Make sure you're using the price before tax, not the displayed retail price (some prices include tax).</p>

    <h3>Step 2 — Identify the correct tax rate for the province</h3>
    <p>Use the table above. The rate depends on where the goods or services are delivered, not where your business is registered. Selling from Alberta to a client in Ontario? You charge Ontario's 13% HST.</p>

    <h3>Step 3 — Multiply subtotal by the tax rate</h3>
    <div class="formula">
      Tax = Subtotal × (Rate ÷ 100)<br>
      <code>Example: $1,000 × (5 ÷ 100) = $50 GST</code>
    </div>

    <h3>Step 4 — Add tax to subtotal for the invoice total</h3>
    <div class="formula">
      Total = Subtotal + Tax<br>
      <code>Example: $1,000 + $50 = $1,050 invoice total</code>
    </div>

    <h2>Real Examples by Province</h2>

    <div class="example-box">
      <h4>Example 1 — Ontario (13% HST) on a $2,500 invoice</h4>
      <ol>
        <li>Subtotal: $2,500.00</li>
        <li>HST = $2,500 × 0.13 = <strong>$325.00</strong></li>
        <li>Total Due = $2,500 + $325 = <strong>$2,825.00</strong></li>
      </ol>
    </div>

    <div class="example-box">
      <h4>Example 2 — British Columbia (5% GST + 7% PST) on a $1,500 invoice</h4>
      <ol>
        <li>Subtotal: $1,500.00</li>
        <li>GST = $1,500 × 0.05 = <strong>$75.00</strong></li>
        <li>PST = $1,500 × 0.07 = <strong>$105.00</strong></li>
        <li>Total Due = $1,500 + $75 + $105 = <strong>$1,680.00</strong></li>
      </ol>
    </div>

    <div class="example-box">
      <h4>Example 3 — Quebec (5% GST + 9.975% QST) on a $4,000 invoice</h4>
      <ol>
        <li>Subtotal: $4,000.00</li>
        <li>GST = $4,000 × 0.05 = <strong>$200.00</strong></li>
        <li>QST = $4,000 × 0.09975 = <strong>$399.00</strong></li>
        <li>Total Due = $4,000 + $200 + $399 = <strong>$4,599.00</strong></li>
      </ol>
    </div>

    <h2>What Must Appear on a Canadian Invoice?</h2>
    <p>The CRA requires all GST/HST registered businesses to include the following on every invoice:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Your business name and address</li>
      <li>Your <strong>GST/HST registration number</strong> (mandatory)</li>
      <li>Invoice date</li>
      <li>The buyer's name (or business name)</li>
      <li>A description of the goods or services</li>
      <li>The amount paid (subtotal before tax)</li>
      <li>The tax rate applied and the tax amount</li>
      <li>The total amount due</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Missing the GST/HST number is the most common compliance failure. Without it, your client cannot claim Input Tax Credits on their own return, and they may refuse to pay until you fix the invoice.</p>

    <h2>Calculating GST in Reverse (When the Total Includes Tax)</h2>
    <p>Sometimes you have an after-tax total and need to find the pre-tax amount and the tax. The formula is:</p>
    <div class="formula">
      Subtotal = Total ÷ (1 + Rate)<br>
      Tax = Total - Subtotal<br>
      <code>Example: $1,050 ÷ 1.05 = $1,000 subtotal, $50 GST</code>
    </div>
    <p>This is useful when a client gives you a single all-in number and you need to break it apart for accounting.</p>

    <h2>Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Using the wrong rate</strong> — always use the destination province, not your home province.</li>
      <li><strong>Charging GST when you shouldn't</strong> — if your annual revenue is below $30,000, GST registration is optional. Don't collect tax you can't remit.</li>
      <li><strong>Forgetting your GST number</strong> — without it, the invoice is not CRA-compliant.</li>
      <li><strong>Mixing up HST and GST</strong> — provinces with HST do not also charge GST separately. It's one combined rate.</li>
      <li><strong>Rounding errors</strong> — calculate to two decimal places only when finalizing the total.</li>
    </ul>

